      "text": "-fast\n-unique\n-short (5-7)",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "-fast\n-unique\n-short (5-7)",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "ap3MoTmf0MxWY-2xJ6Wm4",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1244.251226202529,
      "y": 1766.2220370085076,
      "width": 1147.8926013344421,
      "height": 1075,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "ab",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1789583297,
      "version": 2235,
      "versionNonce": 1960951559,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [
        {
          "id": "S0xBlFFGgCqLea6JvjvB6",
          "type": "arrow"
        },
        {
          "id": "B9QkxZIQnPthLJxjiXcMi",
          "type": "arrow"
        }
      ],
      "updated": 1782652935806,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "1. prefix of the long url\n    - bad approach as many will share common prefix\n\n\n\n2. random number generator 10^9 \n\nsince we are needed to generate 1B urls the random number id must be at least 1B = 10^9\nor 10 characters are needed for this operation, but we can shorten it further\n\nBase 62 encoding 0-9, A-Z, a-z means 10->A, 11->B can generate upto 62 encodings\n-lets choose 6 between 5-7\n-62^6 = 56 Billion -> Collision probability is still high\n-Birthday Paradox -> 23 people in a room chances that 2 people have same bday > 50% out of 365 days\n-880k collisions in 1 billion \n-we need to check for collision first\n\n\n3. Hash the long url\n- md5(long url) -> hash -> [take 6 characters or truncate the long hash] -> base62(hash)\nmd5 returns -> MD5: 06d68bdbae12cb1837095f97771be94c (take 6) -> base62\n- same as above\n\n\n\n4. Counter\n- no need to check for collisions\n- incrementing a counter -> calculate base62 -> Example -> 11157 resolves to 2TX\n- predictability which is bad for security\n    to prevent\n        - \"warning, don't shorten private urls\"\n        - rate limiting (so that hackers can't just come and scrape the remaing long urls after figuring\nour how may have been generated till now)\n        - bijective function (basically give one to one mapping)\n            -sqids.org (takes a number and returns a base62 encoded string)\n\n\n5. 4's Evolved approach is the zookeeper approach, where the counters are basically assigned to each\nservers \n1 - 1M 1st\n2 - 2M 2nd\n3 - 3M 3rd\n",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "1. prefix of the long url\n    - bad approach as many will share common prefix\n\n\n\n2. random number generator 10^9 \n\nsince we are needed to generate 1B urls the random number id must be at least 1B = 10^9\nor 10 characters are needed for this operation, but we can shorten it further\n\nBase 62 encoding 0-9, A-Z, a-z means 10->A, 11->B can generate upto 62 encodings\n-lets choose 6 between 5-7\n-62^6 = 56 Billion -> Collision probability is still high\n-Birthday Paradox -> 23 people in a room chances that 2 people have same bday > 50% out of 365 days\n-880k collisions in 1 billion \n-we need to check for collision first\n\n\n3. Hash the long url\n- md5(long url) -> hash -> [take 6 characters or truncate the long hash] -> base62(hash)\nmd5 returns -> MD5: 06d68bdbae12cb1837095f97771be94c (take 6) -> base62\n- same as above\n\n\n\n4. Counter\n- no need to check for collisions\n- incrementing a counter -> calculate base62 -> Example -> 11157 resolves to 2TX\n- predictability which is bad for security\n    to prevent\n        - \"warning, don't shorten private urls\"\n        - rate limiting (so that hackers can't just come and scrape the remaing long urls after figuring our how may have been generated till now)\n        - bijective function (basically give one to one mapping)\n            -sqids.org (takes a number and returns a base62 encoded string)\n\n\n5. 4's Evolved approach is the zookeeper approach, where the counters are basically assigned to each servers \n1 - 1M 1st\n2 - 2M 2nd\n3 - 3M 3rd\n",
      "autoResize": false,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
